{
  "texts": [
    "We use Google's Pub/Sub.",
    "Skeletons were generated using a graph-based generalization of the TEASAR algorithm 43 using L2 chunks.",
    "For a given root ID, we query the ChunkedGraph for its component L2 IDs and the list of which L2 chunks are directly adjacent to others, either via supervoxels that spanned chunk boundaries or proofreading edits that introduced edges between chunks.",
    "We next query the L2-Cache to identify the representative coordinate (and other properties) for each L2 ID and use this information to generate a graph where each vertex is a single L2 chunk and edges have a weight given by the distance between representative coordinates of adjacent chunks.",
    "Following the TEASAR algorithm, we identify a root node (for example, the closest vertex to a cell body centroid or the base of the axon from a peripheral sensory neuron) and find the most distant vertex on the graph."
  ]
}